munity-based research is new, and their conclusion that externally generated, imposed structure impedes community autonomy and responsibility is well supported. The book significantly expands the established theoretical framework of action-research and offers an exciting alternative to existing models of community development.The Company of Neighbours demonstrates a valuable approach for researchers, social workers, educators, and geographers in facilitating the collective efforts of people in local communities to shape the conditions of their own lives. With a new farmer's market, a museum in the renovated train station, youth programs, and an invigorated Business Improvement Association, Hespeler is well on its way to a new identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAction researchzOntariozHespelervCase studies. 0aAction researchzOntariozHespeler. 0aCommunity developmentzOntariozHespelervCase studies. 0aEvaluation research (Social action programs)vCase studies. 0aSocial servicexResearchzOntariozHespelervCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBanks, C. Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMangan, J. Marshall, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMangan, J. Marshall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268086940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442680869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442680869.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPA